<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   * Samper Promises To `Pay Debt Owed' Women </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P20416 </F>
<F P=103> 94P20416 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:CSO 

  [Editorial Report] During four campaign stops in Cali, 
Liberal Party presidential hopeful Ernesto Samper said that, if 
elected, he will "pay the debt owed to Colombian women." 
Speaking to various female audiences ranging from professionals 
to factory workers, Samper said he would adopt a policy of 
"positive discrimination" in favor of women whereby a woman 
would be given preference over a man in situations where equally 
qualified male and female candidates are being considered for a 
job or promotion. Samper's seven-point program to benefit women 
would include: Formulation of a National Development Plan to 
promote greater opportunities and equality for women; measures 
to reduce unemployment among women, especially those between 
25-35 years of age; a promise that, by the end of his term, 
women would occupy half of the managerial and advisory positions 
in his government; flexibility in work schedules to accommodate 
the needs of working mothers; better training for child-care 
providers to improve their wage status; more severe punishment 
for violence against women; and subsidies to help female heads 
of households. 
  During one address to a group of factory workers, most of 
whom were single mothers, Samper also said his administration 
would provide 500,000 subsidized housing units and implement a 
program of microenterprises for female heads of households. 
(Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO 4 Feb 94 p 9A; 5 Feb 94 p 7A; EL 
ESPECTADOR 4 Feb 94 p 5A) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

