<H3> <TI>   GDP Hits Record High of $446 Billion </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2002000594 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 
19 Feb 94 p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY2002000594 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Last year, after three years of recession, the 
country's GDP reached the highest level in history. The accrued 
total of goods and services produced by the country during that 
year reached $446 billion, indicating a growth of 4.96 percent 
compared to 1992. The expansion represents a real growth of 
23.54 percent compared to the GDP of 1980, which closed the 
expansionist cycle registered throughout the 1970's. During the 
same period, however, the population increased 28.2 percent, 
which means that per capita income fell 3.7 percent despite the 
improvement of 2.97 percent registered last year compared with 
1992. The growth of the 1993 GDP, compared with 1992, was 
attributed to the recovery of the mean real productivity index, 
which grew nearly 10 percent, the stability of employment 
levels, and a 9-percent increase in industrial production. 

</TEXT>

