<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Coffee Industry Claims $8.5 Million Monthly Loss </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1902132194 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 
17 Feb 94 p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY1902132194 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sao Paulo -- The government policy to improve the 
price of green coffee beans in the international market through 
the retention of 20 percent of the harvest has worsened the 
coffee producers' crisis, according to Americo Sato, president 
of the Brazilian Coffee Industry Association [Associacao 
Brasileira da Industria do Cafe -- Abic]. Sato says that the 
auctions carried out by the government with the objective of 
increasing coffee quotations abroad also increased prices in the 
domestic market. Sato said that the average annual quotations in 
dollars of green coffee beans suffered a variation of 34.56 
percent in 1993 in comparison with 1992, or 28.8 percent above 
the IGP-M [Market Prices General Index] of the same period. The 
average price adjustment in dollars during 1993 was 31.69 
percent. This difference, Sato said, caused a monthly loss of 
$8.5 million for the coffee industry. 
  In 1993 coffee production increased only 1.4 percent in 
comparison with the previous year while the initial forecast was 
a 4.6 percent increase. The sales volume during the second half 
of the year remained 2.5 percent below the average sales for the 
period. "The sharp increase in the price of coffee, which is 
responsible for 45 percent of the costs of the industry, has 
prompted a coffee price increase above the inflation which, 
together with the loss of the purchasing power, caused an 
immediate reduction of consumption," Sato said. 
  Consumption -- According to Abic, total consumption of 
roasted and ground coffee in the domestic market during 1993 was 
not greater than 9.3 million bags, which is equivalent to an 
annual consumption of 2.9 kg per capita. The Abic had expected a 
consumption of 9.5 million bags or 3 kg per capita. "Many coffee 
companies have already stopped their activities. Unless the 
government establishes a partnership with the coffee industry, 
with some mechanisms to regulate the price of the raw material, 
the crisis in the coffee industry will become worse during the 
present year," Sato said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-33520 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat037__a94014" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-037-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 February 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1702224794 FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>
<F P=103> PY1702224794 </F>
<F P=104>  FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>



<TEXT>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities in Brazil monitored through 17 
February. 
  Collection of the IPMF, provisional tax on financial 
operations, during its first month was $336.1 million (about 
131.3 billion cruzeiros), which is below the estimated $400 
million per month. (Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in 
Portuguese 8 Feb 94 Business and Finance Section p 3) 
  The Brazilian Petroleum Corporation, Petrobras, showed a 
$666 
million net profit in 1993, an increase of 1,089 percent 
compared with 1992. The government's debt with the company 
dropped $366 million. The total debt now amounts to $3.358 
billion. (Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 10 Feb 
94 Business and Finance Section p 5) 
  The Planning Secretariat reported that at least 40 of the 
108 
state-owned companies, including Petrobras, in 1993 surpassed 
the budget limitations set for them by Congress. Expenses 
surpassed the investment ceiling by 13.9 percent. (Rio de 
Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 10 Feb 94 Business and 
Finance Section p 4) 
  The government is spending $1.2 billion per year to maintain 
15 unfinished hydroelectric and thermoelectric plants. A study 
by the Andersen Consulting firm shows that each 1,000 megawatts 
of unfinished plant costs $100 million. Besides this, $12.3 
billion already has been invested in these plants. The Angra-2 
nuclear plant's expenses alone already have hit $2.6 billion. 
(Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 13 Feb 94 
Business and Finance Section p 15) 

</TEXT>

