<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Discloses Internal Crisis Over Revision </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2402020394 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 
23 Feb 94 p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY2402020394 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brasilia -- The PT [Workers Party] bloc yesterday 
unanimously decided to disclose the internal crisis this party 
is experiencing. In a harsh note approved by all those 
legislators who were present, the PT bloc voiced its 
disagreement with the decision of the party leadership to ban 
their participation in the constitutional revision, and held the 
PT executive board responsible for any problems the PT's absence 
may cause for the social and individual rights attained by the 
National Constituent Assembly. PT leader Jose Fortunatti 
asserted: "If the executive board has banned us from voting, it 
has to assume the responsibility for this." 
  According to Fortunatti, the entire federal bloc was upset 
by 
the executive board's prohibition, regarded as an inappropriate 
and authoritarian interference. Fortunatti commented: "So far, 
most of the bloc has maintained a cautious attitude." 
Fortunatti noted, however, that the unrest was obvious. From 
the cautious attitude -- many remain silent during a crisis -- 
the bloc decided to make public its disagreement with the party 
leadership. Fortunatti added: "The bloc unanimously rejects 
the executive board's decision to not participate in the 
constitutional revision." 
  Senator Eduardo Suplicy sees no other alternative for the 
party leadership than to yield to the pressure being excerted by 
the PT bloc. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

