<F P=103> PA2102044294 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 20 Feb (PL) -- President Fidel Castro has 
met with two Chilean legislators of the ruling Christian 
Democratic Party who are currently on a working visit to Cuba, 
the weekly Sunday newspaper JUVENTUD REBELDE reported today. 
  The report said that the Chilean legislators who met with 
Castro were Senator Carmen Frei and Deputy Eugenio Ortega. 
  The report added that aspects concerning bilateral relations 
were reviewed during the meeting, confirming advancements made 
in common interest areas. 
  Cuba and Chile broke diplomatic relations on 11 September 
1973 when constitutional president Salvador Allende was 
overthrown in a bloody coup d'etat headed by General Augusto 
Pinochet. 
  Relations between the two nations are currently at a 
consular 
level. 

