<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister on Renewing Diplomatic Ties With Chile </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2402044194 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1455 GMT 20 Feb 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2402044194 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 20 Feb (PL) -- Foreign Minister Roberto 
Robaina has asserted that the renewal of diplomatic relations 
between his country and Chile will ensue when it is most 
appropriate for the latter. He added that Cuba does not wish to 
hasten the formalization of such ties. 
  Robaina made these statements and answered questions posed 
by 
reporters at an improvised news conference last night. He had 
just ended a tour of the central provinces, where he was 
accompanied by the diplomatic corps accredited in Havana. 
  We are not in a hurry or insisting on actions that are 
beyond 
what life itself imposes on all the countries, he said. 
  Regarding Chile and any other country with which we are 
furthering talks to renew diplomatic relations, I would rather 
maintain the same attitude we had with Colombia, Robaina stated. 
  The appropriate time appeared when life itself advised that 
the renewal of relations was desirable, Robaina said in 
reference to the recent renewal of ambassadorial-level relations 
between Colombian and the island. 
  Cuban-Chilean relations were interrupted on 11 September 
1973, when a bloody military coup, headed by General Augusto 
Pinochet, toppled constitutional President Salvador Allende. 
  Currently, bilateral ties are at a consular level. 

</TEXT>

