<F P=100> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   MOP Supports Aristide Plan, 29 Mar Return </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2502000994 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1130 
GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2502000994 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] The Movement for the Organization of the Country 
[MOP] has come out against the accusations of intransigence and 
bad faith brought against the Haitian head of state. President 
Aristide cannot be held responsible for the failures already 
recorded. [passage omitted] 
  The party is convinced that one cannot support the return of 
President Aristide while seeking the best way to implement 
Article 148 of the Constitution [which provides for assumption 
of power by the prime minister in the event the president of the 
Republic is unavailable]. Likewise, one cannot be opposed to the 
bloody 30 September coup d'etat and at the same time support the 
clean-sweep policy or reactivation of Article 149 [which 
provides for the Court of Cassation president to act as 
provisional president of the country pending new presidential 
elections within 45 to 90 days]. [passage omitted] 
  The MOP, which is not promoting any candidacy for the post 
of 
prime minister at this time, urges the entire diplomatic sector 
to unite in demanding respect for the Constitution, the 
commitments made at Governors Island, the end of repression, 
full enjoyment of public liberties, safety guarantees for all, 
the normalization of institutions, and the return of President 
Aristide on 29 March so he can complete his constitutional 
mandate. This is not a difficult solution to enact. 
  The year 2004 [marking the bicentennial of Haiti's 
independence] will soon be here. So let us make this 29 March 
the starting point for preparation of a grand celebration of the 
bicentennial of national independence. 
  MOP leader Gesner Comeau supports the counterproposal sent 
to 
UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali by President Aristide. 
This new plan worked out by the head of state provides for his 
return to Haiti during the 10 days that follow the appointment 
of the new prime minister. Let us listen to Gesner Comeau. 
  [Begin recording, in Creole] I think that if such a plan is 
applied, it would be perfect and in the interest of the waiting 
Haitian people. [passage omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

