<F P=100> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Santa Ana Prison Take Over Continues Without Solution </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2402195594 San Salvador Radio Cadena YSU in Spanish 1800 
GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2402195594 </F>
<F P=104>  San Salvador Radio Cadena YSU </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Alejandro Arturo Flores in Santa Ana; from the </F>
"YSU Radio News" newscast] 
  [Excerpt] The takeover of the western penal facility by 
numerous inmates is into its fourth hour without any sign of a 
solution. So far two people are reported dead and two injured. 
We shall now hear from Gabriel Abraham Paniagua, president of 
the political committee of Armed Forces prisoners, who was 
wounded in his left arm. 
  [Begin recording] [Paniagua] Our people began to arm 
themselves with pieces of sharp steel. 
  [Flores] What do the inmates want? 
  [Panigua] The problem is that the people up front saw the 
soldiers fighting so the rest joined in. The other inmates 
joined in, although they normally do not bother anyone, but they 
were wounded so they joined in the fight against those from 
Gotera. They want to kill them because the problem is that if 
these people are left alive and we are transferred, then they 
will kill us in the other jail. Do you understand? That is why 
the inmates do not want to leave these types alive. 
  Regrettably, the National Guard troops only have to knock 
the 
doors down. We are a disciplined group who obey prison 
regulations. You understand? When I get back, if things have 
calmed down, just as we promised, those who have armed 
themselves will turn over their pocket knives at the front door. 
As you can see, we do not bother anyone. We live for our work 
and our families. We would have preferred some warning 
because... [pauses] [words indistinct] thefts and stabbings have 
increased these past few days. Recently, seven inmates were 
wounded. [end recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

