<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Marcos: 50 Percent of Demands Resolved </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2502141794 Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 
0435 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2502141794 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City XEW Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Statement by Subcommander Marcos, of the Zapatist National </F>
Liberation Army, on talks with the Mexican Government, in San 
Cristobal de las Casas on 24 February; from the "24 Hours" 
newscast -- recorded] 
  [Text] I speak on behalf of the Zapatist National 
Liberation Army [EZLN] to inform the people of Mexico, the 
people and the governments of the world, and the national and 
foreign media about the results of today's meeting with National 
Mediation Commissioner Bishop Samuel Ruiz Garcia and Manuel 
Camacho Solis, national commissioner for peace and 
reconciliation in Chiapas. 
  We have resolved 50 percent of the listed demands. We have 
already received a satisfactory response to the following points 
included on the list of demands presented by the Indian 
Revolutionary Clandestine Committee -- General Command of the 
EZLN. 
  One of these points calls for the electrification of the 
Indian communities and the redistribution of federal investments 
in the State of Chiapas. Another point deals with the impact of 
the free trade agreement on the Indian communities. Another 
point has to do with health, truthful information -- as we 
reported yesterday -- housing, education -- which involves the 
construction of schools, school equipment, and the availability 
of teachers -- obligatory and official bilingual education in 
the Indian communities, respect for Indian traditions and 
culture, punishment for anyone discriminating or showing 
contempt for the Indians, the food problem, economic support for 
the victims of the war and for the widows and orphans of the 
conflict, the demands of the women on what should be done so 
that the Indians may live in peace, the multiplication and 
strengthening of nongovernment human rights organizations, the 
need to form -- at the adequate moment -- a national peace 
commission with justice and honor that will be in charge of 
following up on the agreements reached during these 
negotiations, and the channeling of humanitarian aid to the 
conflict zone through the authentic representatives of the 
Indian communities. This is the last point on which we agreed. 
  These are the agreements we have reached so far. I repeat: 
Fifty percent of the demands presented by the committee have 
been satisfactorily met by the commissioner. 

</TEXT>

