<F P=101> Bolivia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Police Attache Appointment to Embassy in U.S. Questioned </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2202181794 La Paz Television Nacional Network in Spanish 
1700 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY2202181794 </F>
<F P=104>  La Paz Television Nacional Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] So far it is a rumor: Colonel German Linares may 
be appointed police attache to the Bolivian Embassy in 
Washington. The Bolivian Foreign Ministry has not confirmed this 
rumor. Anyway, Linares cannot be appointed as attache until his 
pending trial is resolved in Bolivia. The facts were made public 
thanks to Senator Andres Solis Rada. 
  Ten years ago, in 1984, a lawsuit was filed against a long 
list of individuals accused of being involved in the kidnapping 
of the then-president of the Republic, Hernan Siles Suazo. The 
name of Col. German Linares is on the list and he is allegedly 
one of the main individuals responsible for that criminal action 
and the coup attempt. However, the trial was paralyzed a long 
time like many other lawsuits that sleep in the courtrooms of 
our country. 
  Solis Rada, alarmed at the possibility that Linares might be 
appointed to a diplomatic post, remembered the case and asked 
District Attorney Javier Dipps to reactivate the trial. 
Therefore, this not only means that Col. Linares cannot be a 
diplomat, but he cannot even leave the country. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

