<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Senate Vote on Patent Law Expected After Mid-1994 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2502014594 Sao Paulo FOLHA DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 23 
Feb 94 Section 1 p 4 </F>

<F P=103> PY2502014594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo FOLHA DE SAO PAULO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brasilia -- Industry, Commerce, and Tourism Minister 
Elcio Alvares estimates that the draft patent law, which will 
regulate the protection of industrial property in the country, 
will not be voted on by Congress until the second half of 1994. 
The United States is threatening to impose trade sanctions on 
Brazil if measures designed to protect industrial property are 
not approved by 28 February. 
  The Brazilian Government is seeking to avert U.S. 
retaliatory 
measures by proposing amendments to the draft patent law, which 
has been sitting in the Senate for eight months. Alvares is 
scheduled to talk tomorrow with Senator Beni Veras (Brazilian 
Social Democracy Party -- Ceara State), who was confirmed 
yesterday as rapporteur of the draft law at the Senate Economic 
Affairs Committee, to persuade him about the need to introduce 
changes to the draft approved by the Chamber of Deputies in June 
1993. 

</TEXT>

