<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   EZLN, Government Reach Agreements on 5 Points </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2402153094 Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2402153094 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Francisco Rubio in Chiapas from the "First Thing </F>
in the Morning" newscast; passages within quotation marks 
recorded] 
  [Text] Agreements have already been reached on five points, 
which constitute one-fourth of the neo-Zapatists' [as heard] 
demands. 
  [Zapatist Subcommander Marcos] "So far, we have received 
satisfactory replies to our demands on the following points: 
health, education, true and timely information, housing, and 
respect for culture, traditions, rights, and the dignity of the 
Indian groups in Mexico." 
  Other, more complex demands which were not mentioned will be 
submitted to advisory groups for study, and, even Marcos has 
admitted, there are other proposals that go beyond the 
possibilities of these negotiations. 
  [Subcommander Marcos] "Let it be understood that what the 
Zapatist National Liberation Army [EZLN] wants is that just like 
the war was decided in a democratic manner, peace must 
necessarily follow the same democratic procedure." 
  The rebel subcommander and EZLN delegates are not rushing to 
reach definite agreements. 
  [Subcommander Marcos] "You must return to your areas; you 
must return to your committees and explain to your companions 
the proposals you have received regarding the points which 
started our movement on 1 January 1994. The communities will 
then decide yes or no." 
  [Peace Commissioner Manuel Camacho Solis] "We are making 
much 
faster progress in discussing these problems than I expected at 
the beginning of these meetings." 
  Camacho Solis announced he will follow a similar process. 
  [Camacho Solis] "I will report to the president of the 
republic on each one of the points we have agreed on. I will 
also report to the mixed commission of senators and deputies, 
and I will seek to report to the main political forces 
[pauses]... to all the political forces of the country so there 
will be a broad consensus." 
  New faces were seen during the third day of negotiations in 
San Cristobal de las Casas. These included Monterrey Archbishop 
Adolfo Suarez; Oaxaca Archbishop Hector Gonzalez; and Bishops 
Carlos Talavera from (Cuatzacualcos), Felipe Aguirre from Tuxtla 
Gutierrez, and Felipe Arismendi from Tapachula. They are all 
members of a special commission of the Mexican Bishops 
Conference, which is following the peace process. They will meet 
with political parties representatives and leaders of 
nongovernmental organizations. 
  (Arturo Warman), ombudsman for agrarian affairs, was also 
seen here. He is studying the possible juridical modifications 
that will result from agreements over the land problems. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

