<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   World Bank Group Grants Aid for Autonomy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2801144494 Paris AFP in English 1434 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2801144494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, Jan 28 (AFP) -- The World Bank's 
consultative group on development of the West Bank and Gaza 
decided Friday [January 28] to grant budgetary aid on behalf of 
Palestinian autonomy for this year, the World Bank announced in 
Paris. 
  It said the group members would provide "more than 120 
million dollars to cover the budget deficit of 158 million 
dollars" in connection with Palestinian autonomy this year. 
  The donors -- including the European Community, the United 
States, Japan and some Arab countries -- also agreed to the 
broad outlines of expenditures and receipts contained in the 
first Palestinian budget, developed by the Palestinian Economic 
Council for Reconstruction and Development, the announcement 
said. 
  The consultative group, grouping 24 countries and five 
international institutions, was supposed to cover the entire 
budget deficit. Palestinian delegation head Nabil Kassir told 
correspondents that "We did not get everything we need to ensure 
economic stability. But we did not come out so badly." 
  The donors' meeting was held Thursday and Friday at the 
World 
Bank's European headquarters in Paris. 

</TEXT>

