<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   PFLP, DFLP Deny Intention To Move Headquarters </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN3001093794 Amman AL-RA'Y in Arabic 30 Jan 94 p 25 </F>
<F P=103> JN3001093794 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AL-RA'Y </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by 'Awdah 'Awdah] </F>
  [Text] The Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine 
[PFLP] has denied that it is about to move its headquarters from 
Damascus to Baghdad. 
  The PFLP and the Democratic Front for the Liberation of 
Palestine [DFLP], as well as other factions, moved their 
headquarters from Beirut to Damascus after the Palestinian 
resistance evacuated Beirut in September 1982, while Fatah and 
other factions moved from Beirut to Tunis. 
  Following his return from Baghdad a few days ago, PFLP 
Political Bureau member 'Abd-al-Rahim Malluh told AL-RA'Y that 
the PFLP delegation's visit to Baghdad had nothing to do with 
this subject, and said the PFLP's main office is still in 
Damascus. 
  Malluh denied that the opposition factions, including the 
PFLP, are facing harassment by the Syrian leadership. 
  He described the press reports published by London 
newspapers 
on moving the PFLP headquarters from Damascus to Baghdad as 
completely untrue, and said the front has the right to be 
present in the Arab states bordering Palestine. 
  He said that cooperation and coordination between the 
Palestinian opposition forces and the Syrian leadership 
continue, based on their position which calls for full Israeli 
withdrawal from the occupied Palestinian and Arab territories, 
and their joint position on the dangers of self-rule because it 
is unfair to the Palestinian national rights. 
  Meanwhile, a DFLP official said he expects a DFLP delegation 
to visit the Iraqi capital within 10 days. DFLP Political 
Bureau member Saji Salamah denied any intention to move the 
front's headquarters from Damascus to Baghdad, and emphasized 
that the DFLP delegation's visit to Baghdad had been decided a 
long time ago. 
  The visits by the PFLP and DFLP delegations to Baghdad are 
the first since the Syrian-U.S. summit in Geneva. 
  Fatah and other factions have announced that they will move 
their headquarters to the self-rule region after Israel's 
withdrawal from Gaza and Jericho, expected to be completed next 
April. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

