<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Committee To Monitor Human Rights Violations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2801130894 Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ in Hebrew 28 Jan 94 p A4 </F>
<F P=103> TA2801130894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Yosi Torpstein] </F>
  [Excerpt] A seminar on democracy and human rights 
organized by the Center for the Protection of Liberties, 
identified with the Democratic Front for the Liberation of 
Palestine [DFLP], has, for the first time ever, decided to 
establish a committee in the territories to monitor human rights 
violations against Palestinians by fellow Palestinians. 
  Presenting the idea, Dr. Mahmad Jadallah, one of the most 
prominent DFLP activists, said that in view of the feared human 
rights violations against Palestinians not only by Israel but 
also by the Palestinian national government that will be 
established in the territories, "someone must try to stop 
irregularities and violations of human rights by Palestinians, 
even if this is only done by words." 
  The seminar, held yesterday at the al-Watani Hotel in East 
Jerusalem, dealt with issues on the current agenda of 
Palestinian society involving its fears with regard to the 
future. Among other things, the participants discussed 
relations between the individual and the Palestinian government 
that will be established in the territories, the status and role 
of human rights watch organizations in relation to that 
government, the status of Palestinian women, and the proposed 
constitution for the Palestinian government. 
  In the discussions, sharp criticism was leveled at the PLO 
leadership for signing the Oslo agreement; for its lack of 
awareness of the need to teach democratic values in schools and 
other institutions; and for other negative phenomena in the 
territories, such as the murder of innocent people. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

