<F P=100> ARAB AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Algeria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Suspension Reports Denied </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3101093794 Algiers Radio Algiers Network in Arabic 0600 
GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3101093794 </F>
<F P=104>  Algiers Radio Algiers Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Some Western newspapers, primary among which is the 
French LE MONDE, have disseminated a report that Algeria has 
suspended payment on external debt servicing. This report was 
denied yesterday by sources close to the government. The 
sources said that Algeria has been continuing to service its 
foreign debt. Nasira Bouzid reports: 
  [Bouzid] Algeria continues payment of its external debts by 
the required time. Sources close to the prime minister's office 
have told APS that Algeria has paid in succession $900 million 
and $600 million as debt principal and services, for the 
payments due in December last and this month, January, alone. 
Likewise, in December 1992 and January 1993, Algeria paid in 
succession $911 million and $694 million. 
  The same sources said that the reorganization of debt 
management procedures in order to improve them had led to a 
purely administrative delay. The prime minister's office 
stressed that Algeria continues to make all efforts to preserve 
its policy of respect for foreign commitments. The same sources 
thereby denied the reports carried by some Western newspapers, 
especially LE MONDE, which had a headline on its front page 
yesterday saying: Algeria Suspends Payment of its External Debt. 
The government sources described these reports as groundless. 

</TEXT>

