<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Sources' Note U.S. Cooperation Plan for Region </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2901150894 Cairo AL-SHA'B in Arabic 25 Jan 94 p 7 </F>
<F P=103> NC2901150894 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo AL-SHA'B </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Mahmud Bakri] </F>
  [Text] Political sources have told AL-SHA'B that during his 
tour of the region U.S. Commerce Secretary Ronald Brown has 
discussed a plan for cooperation among Egypt, Israel, Saudi 
Arabia, and Jordan. Brown met with President Husni Mubarak 
Thursday to discuss the details of the U.S. economic plan, which 
includes the following points: 
  1. Establishing free trade between Israel and the three Arab 
countries through trade agreements between governments. The 
agreements will involve Israeli commodities and products tha? 
can be exported to the three Arab markets, and commodities and 
products of the three Arab countries that can be exported to 
Israel. 
  2. Establishing banking cooperation between the three Arab 
countries and Israel to finance a number of common commercial, 
agricultural, and industrial projects. 
  3. Abolishing restrictions imposed on the private sectors in 
the three Arab countries concerning trade and establishment of 
joint ventures, whether in Israel or in the Arab countries. 
  4. Setting up a four-way committee, with the possibility of 
Palestinians joining it, to study duties on commodities 
exchanged among the four countries. 
  The U.S. plan stresses the need to begin steps for economic 
cooperation in March or April. It says the agreements will 
support the bases of the ongoing peace process. Brown said 
during his talks with President Mubarak that U.S. President Bill 
Clinton is interested in seeing the plan implemented. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

