<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Incidents </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2901204894 Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1900 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2901204894 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1900 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Three IDF [Israel Defense Forces] soldiers were 
slightly injured by a grenade thrown at them in Rafah this 
afternoon. Our army affairs correspondent Alon Ben-David 
reports that the three were evacuated to hospital, and IDF 
troops launched searches for the perpetrators. 
  Two Arab residents were wounded by soldiers gunfire in Gaza 
this afternoon. Our correspondent Shlomi Eldar reports that as 
a soccer game between Gaza and Rafah teams was in progress, IDF 
soldiers entered the field to pursue an armed suspect. While in 
pursuit, they were pelted with stones by the spectators. 
  [Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew at 1700 GMT on 29 January 
adds: "Last night in Rafah, IDF soldiers captured a Hamas 
[Islamic Resistance Movement] terrorist carrying a Kalashnikov 
and ammunition. 
  ["A Molotov cocktail was thrown at a Border Police patrol 
near Abu-Dis tonight. The bottle shattered and ignited, but no 
one was hurt and no damage was caused."] 
  Fatah figures have expressed satisfaction with the results 
of 
the elections to the Gaza Strip Engineers Association, in which 
Fatah representatives were elected to four out of the nine 
seats, with Islamic Jihad and Hamas, which ran on a joint list, 
gaining the other four seats. [The ninth seat is to be held by 
rotation.] The elected chairman is Sa'id Khurama from Fatah. 
Our correspondent in the south notes that because of Fatah's 
dire financial condition, by comparison to other organizations, 
Fatah had been unable to achieve better results in the election 
campaign, with many candidates defecting to Hamas as a result of 
Fatah's inability to pay salaries. 

</TEXT>

