<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jordanian Diplomat Assassinated in Beirut 29 Jan </TI></H3>
<H4>   Foreign Ministry Issues Statement </H4>
<F P=102> JN2901125794 Amman Radio Jordan Network in Arabic 1200 GMT 
29 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2901125794 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Radio Jordan Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Acting Prime Minister Dr. Ma'n Abu-Nuwar 
announces to the Jordanian family, with great sorrow and 
sadness, the martyrdom of Jordanian diplomat Na'ib 'Umran 
al-Ma'ayitah, first secretary at the Jordanian Embassy in 
Beirut, who was the target of a treacherous attack in Beirut 
today. [passage omitted] 
  In another development, the Foreign Ministry issued a 
statement on this sinful action. Following is the text of the 
statement: 
  We received with great sorrow and pain the news about the 
martyrdom of one of Jordan's sons, Na'ib 'Umran al-Ma'ayitah, 
the counselor at the Jordanian Embassy in Beirut, this morning 
following a sinful attack while he was on his way from his 
residence to his office at the embassy. 
  While condemning this brutal attack, the Jordanian 
Government 
will embark on the necessary measures to learn about the 
circumstances surrounding the attack, and efforts to pursue the 
terrorists and criminals who are responsible for this criminal 
action, regardless of the party to which they belong. 
  The Jordanian Government also condemns all forms of 
terrorism 
that target innocent peoples. 
  Lebanese foreign and interior ministers, accompanied by 
commander of public security and other Lebanese officials, 
called on the Jordanian Embassy in Beirut, and expressed their 
denunciation of this criminal action and their full readiness to 
pursue and identify the perpetrators. 
  An honorary mission left for Beirut in a special airplane to 
escort the body of the deceased back home. 

</TEXT>

