<F P=100> SYRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paper Says Syrian-Israeli Talks `Encouraging' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC3001180294 Paris AFP in English 1715 GMT 30 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC3001180294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Damascus, Jan 30 (AFP) -- The bilateral Arab-Israeli 
peace talks in Washington are proceeding in an "encouraging and 
positive atmosphere," the official AL-THAWRAH daily said here 
Sunday [30 January]. 
  In an editorial, the newspaper said U.S. Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher described the negotiations as "very 
promising," because "he noted how serious the Syrian position 
was." 
  The bilateral talks resumed Monday after a four-month break 
following the signing of the PLO-Israeli autonomy accord in 
September, which Syria condemned, arguing that separate deals 
undermined the Arab negotiating position. 
  "The negotiations will make progress if Israel conforms to 
the requirements of peace, but the search for a settlement will 
go back to square one if the Jewish state continues to stand by 
its previous positions," the newspaper said. 
  On Wednesday Christopher described as "very promising" the 
new format for the negotiations, with meetings restricted to the 
heads of the Israeli, Jordanian, Syrian, Lebanese and 
Palestinian delegations. 

</TEXT>

