<H3> <TI>   Turkish Offer Accepted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA3001200294 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1555 GMT 30 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA3001200294 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, Jan 30 (A.A) -- Iran on Sunday accepted 
Turkey's offer to set up a special committee to investigate 
allegations that civilian villages were hit in Iran's border 
regions during Turkey's air strike on Friday against terrorist 
bases in northern Iraq, near the Turkish border. 
  AA was told by officials at the Iranian Foreign Ministry 
that 
Iran will not "at this point" ask for any compensation. 
  Iran had alleged on Friday that nine civilians from its 
border villages were killed during raids by Turkish war planes 
aiming at the terrorist bases in northern Iraq. 
  The Turkish Foreign Ministry for its part had stated that 
close inspection of the photographs taken of the area where the 
strike was held, showed that no such mistake was made. 

</TEXT>

