<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Comments on Compensation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3101125594 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 1030 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3101125594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Persian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The deputy foreign minister for Asia and Oceania has 
said in a meeting with the Turkish ambassador to Tehran that an 
official apology from the Turkish Government and the payment of 
compensation for losses suffered by the victims of the tragic 
incident on the border between the two countries is the least 
that will be expected by the people of Iran. 
  Mr Borujerdi referred to the visit paid by the Turkish 
consul 
in Orumiyeh to the victims of the incident and said: The 
existence of these witnesses to the bombings must have removed 
any doubts Turkish officials may have had about the bombs 
falling around the Sar-e Dasht area. He added: The Islamic 
Republic of Iran strongly requests that the Turkish Government 
adopt measures ensuring that future military operations by that 
country in northern Iraq will not inflict any harm or damage to 
the Islamic Republic of Iran's borders, even if such operations 
take place close to our country's frontiers. 
  Mr. Haktanir, the Turkish ambassador to Tehran, for his part 
expressed deep regret over the tragic incident and said: The 
Iranian authorities and nation must rest assured that the plans 
of Turkey's military officials were to attack the positions of 
PKK guerrillas inside Iraqi territory, and that was precisely 
why we immediately sent a special fact-finding team to examine 
the situation close up with Iranian officials. He added: The 
Turkish Government will not forego any measure to make up for 
the losses inflicted, and the proposals of the Government of the 
Islamic Republic of Iran will be speedily conveyed to the 
Turkish authorities. 

</TEXT>

