<F P=100> Mauritania </F>
<H3> <TI>   No Overall Majority Reported in Municipal Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2901171894 Rabat Moroccan Kingdom Radio Network in Arabic 
1600 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2901171894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rabat Moroccan Kingdom Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In Mauritania the two main parties were unable to 
obtain an absolute majority in the local elections, which were 
held for the first time yesterday under multiparty conditions. 
The most striking feature of the elections was the failure of 
the candidates to gain the votes needed to prevent the holding 
of a second round of voting, which will take place on 4 February 
in all the municipalities where candidates were unable to gain 
more than 50 percent of the votes cast. 
  According to the official preliminary results, the 
Republican 
Democratic and Social Party and the Union of Democratic Forces 
[UFD] gained an equal number of votes, especially in the capital 
Nouakchott and the financial capital Noudibu. 
  In Nouakchott, the party of Mauritanian President Maaouiya 
Ould Sid Ahmed Taya gained 44.77 percent of the votes cast, 
while its rival the UFD, which is the most important opposition 
grouping, gained 42 percent of the votes in the capital. The 
Union for Democracy and Progress obtained 15 percent of the 
votes cast in a total of 208 municipalities in Mauritania. 

</TEXT>

