<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Peres-'Arafat Talks in Davos </TI></H3>
<H4>   `Final Draft Agreement' Outlined </H4>
<F P=102> JN3101152394 Paris Radio Monte Carlo in Arabic 1200 GMT 31 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN3101152394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio Monte Carlo </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Dispatch by Basim Abu-Sumayyah from the occupied territory] </F>
  [Text] Israeli and Palestinian sources have stressed that 
Israel and the PLO reached a final draft agreement to implement 
the Gaza-Jericho accord yesterday while meeting in Davos. 
Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat and Israeli Foreign 
Minister Shim'on Peres are expected to meet in Cairo in 10 days 
to sign the agreement. 
  Israeli sources said that the two sides are drafting the 
technical details of the agreement, which should begin to be 
implemented within the next two weeks. These sources added that 
the Davos draft agreement includes the following points: 
  -- Israel's demands and security requirements will be 
guaranteed; 
  -- Israel will control road junctions in the Gaza Strip; 
  -- Only Israeli police will carry out searches at the 
border crossings. Palestinian police will be present at these 
crossings; 
  -- The two sides will reach an understanding on the size 
of the Jericho area so that this matter will not constitute an 
obstacle in the talks. Israel will be flexible in this regard; 
  -- The citizens of the self-rule area will be able to move 
freely to the al-Nabi Musa, near Jericho, and al-Maghtis, on the 
Jordan River, to perform religious rites only; 
  -- The Palestinians in Gaza and Jericho will have access 
to the joint recreation area to be built between the Israelis 
and the Palestinians on the Dead Sea; 
  -- The passages leading to these areas will remain under 
Israeli military control; 
  -- Special passages for the self-rule residents to move 
about without restriction will be established. These passages 
will ultimately be linked to a highway linking Amman to the 
self-rule area across the King 'Abdallah Bridge. 
  -- Israel will have the right to protest the entry of 
suspect Palestinians; and 
  -- Special Israeli search rooms will be created at the 
border crossings. The Palestinian police will not be allowed in 
these search rooms. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-33749 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes021yy_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-021 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 February 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Peres-'Arafat Talks in Davos </TI></H3>
<H4>   Sha'th Comments on Talks </H4>
<F P=102> NC3101182994 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1720 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC3101182994 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 31 Jan (MENA)--Nabil Sha'th, Palestinian 
President Yasir 'Arafat's political advisor, arrived in Cairo 
this evening from Switzerland after taking part in the meeting 
between 'Arafat and Israeli Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres in 
Davos. 
  Upon his arrival, Sha'th stated that 'Arafat and Peres will 
meet in Cairo on Sunday [6 February]. He noted that the 
Palestinian and Israeli delegations will meet tomorrow to 
prepare for the 'Arafat-Peres meeting on Sunday. 
  Sha'th expressed his belief that the Davos meeting has made 
some progress with respect to the difficult problems surrounding 
the Gaza-Jericho agreement. 
  He said that if we reach agreement on Sunday, we will have 
overcome the stage of conflicts and advance to the signing of 
the agreement. 
  Sha'th clarified that an international presence at the 
crossings has been ruled out, but it is still our right to 
demand a temporary international presence in Gaza for a period 
of one or two years. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

