<DOCNO> FBIS3-33750 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes021yy_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-021 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 February 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Peres-'Arafat Talks in Davos </TI></H3>
<H4>   PLO Envoy: `Hope on the Horizon' </H4>
<F P=102> JN3101204494 Amman Jordan Television Network in Arabic 1800 
GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN3101204494 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Jordan Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Upon his arrival in Amman today, Palestinian 
Ambassador in Cairo Sa'id Kamal, told our correspondent that 
Israel is still studying the Palestinian paper presented by the 
PLO and that there is hope on the horizon. 
  [Begin recording] [Kamal] I can say that when I left Cairo 
for beloved Amman there was a paper comprising 12 contentious 
points. On the sidelines of the World Economic Forum in Davos, 
it was agreed that brother Abu-'Ammar [Yasir 'Arafat] and the 
Israeli foreign minister should meet to try to overcome these 
points, after Israel had a chance to study them, especially from 
the PLO's point of view. 
  I was somewhat cautious when I learned yesterday about the 
optimistic report that a compromise [previous word in English] 
was reached, because Mr. Rabin holds the reigns and has the 
final say. It became evident that, until this morning, the man 
was still studying the particular issue of security at crossing 
points, which is a sensitive issue to both the Palestinian and 
Israeli sides, as well as to the Jordanian and Egyptian sides. 
  Hence, there is a glimmer of hope on the horizon for another 
meeting before the beginning of the holy month of Ramadan in 
order to formulate the agreement. However, this must be 
preceded by a meeting that solves the problems over the issue of 
crossing points, especially the crossing point at Rafah. This 
is after Rabin announces that he is coming to Cairo, just as he 
announced earlier, to sign the final agreement on security 
preparations and withdrawal within the Gaza Strip and the 
Jericho area. 
  [Reporter] Besides the issue or problem of crossing points, 
are there other problems obstructing the agreement? 
  [Kamal] I believe that there are still stylistic issues 
rather than issues that are particularly sensitive to either 
side or to the Arab side, in general, especially to the Arab 
cordon states. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

