<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Peres-'Arafat Talks in Davos </TI></H3>
<H4>   Peres: Wording Not Yet Finalized </H4>
<F P=102> TA0102060194 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 0505 GMT 1 Feb 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0102060194 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin has said that some 
progress was made in the Davos talks, but no agreement has yet 
been reached between Israel and the PLO. Foreign Minister 
Shim'on Peres said last night that Israel and the PLO have 
overcome two or three of the toughest issues in the 
negotiations. The prime minister was speaking in a conference 
call with the Conference of Presidents of Major American Jewish 
Organizations, while the foreign minister also spoke in a 
conference call, but with Israeli journalists in Washington. 
Arye Golan reports from Washington: 
  [Begin recording] [Golan] Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres 
will start a two-day visit to Washington this afternoon. The 
main event on the first day is a meeting with Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher to update him on the talks with 'Arafat in 
Davos. In a conference call from Florida, where he started his 
U.S. visit, Peres refused to detail the solutions worked out in 
Davos. 
  [Peres] We agreed on the contents, but we have not yet 
reached agreement on the wording. I did not want to draft it 
hastily or without holding consultations at home, because 
telephone consultations have their limitations. Since each word 
is important, I came to the conclusion that before we add our 
signature, it would be best to wait several days until I have 
the opportunity to speak with the prime minister and others 
involved in the talks. This requires a lot of time and 
patience, but I remain firm in my belief that we can reach a 
full agreement, although under no circumstances am I ready to 
say how long it will take. 
  [Golan] Both Prime Minister Rabin, in his conference call 
with the Conference of Presidents of Major American Jewish 
Organizations, and Foreign Minister Peres stress that the 
government will make sure that Israel remains responsible for 
overall security and that the IDF [Israel Defense Forces] will 
protect the settlements. Both promise the government will not 
compromise on security. 
  [Peres] We have not compromised and will not compromise on 
security matters, and we must be extremely careful in wording 
any agreement on security. As I have already said, I prefer to 
go over the draft word by word, because we have reviewed many 
drafts during the negotiating process. I would like the final 
draft to be acceptable to my colleagues, the prime minister in 
particular. 
  [Golan] Before Peres leaves the United States to continue 
the negotiations with 'Arafat in Cairo, he will confer here with 
Senate and House leaders, and tomorrow he will meet with Vice 
President Al Gore and National Security Adviser Anthony Lake. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

