<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Israel, PLO Hold `Top Secret' Talks in Cairo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0102112694 Paris AFP in English 1030 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0102112694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, Feb 1 (AFP) -- Israeli and PLO negotiators 
began top secret negotiations here Tuesday [1 February] on 
finalising an accord on Palestinian autonomy, a Palestinian 
delegation source said. 
  The location and duration of the talks as well as the 
make-up 
of the teams were not revealed. 
  The source said that the meeting was shrouded in the 
"greatest secrecy", and an Israeli diplomat here refused to give 
any details. 
  The talks are to prepare the ground for a meeting between 
Israeli Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres and PLO leader Yasir 
'Arafat here on Sunday. 
  The two reported important progress when they met last 
weekend in Davos, Switzerland, although Israeli officials have 
been stressing that a final agreement will still take several 
weeks. 
  The outstanding disagreements include control of 
international border crossings, the size of the Jericho 
autonomous area and security for Jewish settlements. 
  PLO chief negotiator Nabil Sha'th said Monday that the two 
sides in Davos "managed to resolve all problems concerning Gaza, 
Jericho and the crossing points" but added: "I don't want to be 
too optimistic, because stumbling blocks sometimes emerge for 
reasons beyond our control." 
  He had said the two sides would resume talks in Cairo on 
Tuesday in a bid to resolve remaining differences, but Israeli 
officials said consultations were continuing in Jerusalem and 
the talks were not scheduled to begin. 
  The disagreements have held up the beginning of the Israeli 
withdrawal from Gaza and Jericho, which should have begun on 
December 13 under the Declaration of Principles signed on 
September 13. The handover should be completed by April 13. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

