<F P=100> Inter-Arab Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Arab Maghreb Union Summit Postponed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3101212294 Algiers ENTV Television Network in Arabic 1900 
GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3101212294 </F>
<F P=104>  Algiers ENTV Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Arab Maghreb Union summit, which was due to be 
held on 5 February [in Tunis], has been postponed to a later 
date, according to well-informed sources. This official 
postponement announced by the host country, Tunisia, does not 
cancel the Council of Ministers' meeting of the Arab Maghreb 
Union scheduled for the same day, 5 February, in the Tunisian 
capital. 
  The decision to postpone the summit, which was taken by 
Tunisian President Zine El Abidine Ben Ali, was at the request 
of Mauritanian President Maaouiya Ould Sid Ahmed Taya, in view 
of the current developments on the Mauritanian political scene, 
resulting from the recent municipal elections in that country. 
  This Mauritanian request is not the only reason why the 
summit was postponed, because according to the same source, King 
Hassan II [of Morocco] was going to be represented at this 
summit by an envoy. Moreover, Mr. Mu'ammar al-Qadhdhafi has 
also announced that he will not be attending the summit 
proceedings. Algeria, which took over the chairmanship of the 
union on 1 January 1994, had prepared the proceedings of this 
summit [as heard] and [words indistinct] supported Tunisia's 
request for a postponement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

