<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paper Urges Arab League To Set Rules on Boycott </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0102105794 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0610 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0102105794 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 1 Feb (MENA)--AL-AHRAM has urged the Arab 
League in its upcoming meetings to define the rules concerning 
the economic boycott of Israel in order to maintain a minimum 
degree of Arab unanimity on this issue. 
  In its commentary published today, the paper refers to the 
current controversy over the question of the boycott, which came 
into the open following the signing of the Palestinian-Israeli 
agreement in September. The paper notes that the basic 
prevailing conviction is that a settlement in the region will 
have to lead to normal relations over a certain period of time, 
something that the direct parties to the conflict acknowledged 
from the start when they joined the multilateral talks for 
economic regional cooperation. 
  The paper emphasizes that there was a general conviction 
that 
certain criteria governed the lifting of the different types of 
boycotts as the settlement process progressed, but this 
conviction has been somewhat shaken recently. 

</TEXT>

