<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mufti Wants `Political Islam Groups' in Dialogue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2901213694 Cairo AL-'ARABI in Arabic 24 Jan 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> NC2901213694 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo AL-'ARABI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Muhammad al-Rammah] </F>
  [Text] In exclusive remarks to AL-'ARABI, Mufti of the 
Republic Dr. Muhammad Sayyid Tantawi has called for allowing 
political Islamic groups to participate in the upcoming national 
dialogue. He added: The government's dialogue with political 
parties and youth of various tendencies as well as with any 
group or individual, regardless of their inclination, is a good 
thing. It is required for each side to listen to the views of 
the others in the interest of the country, presuming that the 
intentions are sincere. 
  Asked how the youth branded as "extremists" could be 
represented in the national dialogue, the mufti said: The 
important thing is to start the dialogue. As for the question 
of how, this could be judged by the competent experts who will 
send the invitation. 
  It is worth noting that the mufti took part in a seminar 
held 
at Cairo University on Wednesday. He stressed that all 
religions oppose injustice, whether it is done by the ruler or 
the ruled, noting that corruption cases are widespread in 
society. 

</TEXT>

