<F P=100> OPEC Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kuwaiti Minister: OPEC May Cut Oil Output </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC3001141994 Paris AFP in English 1348 GMT 30 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC3001141994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kuwait City, Jan 30 (AFP) -- OPEC may decide to 
reduce oil production to prop up falling crude prices, at its 
next ministerial meeting scheduled for March 25, Kuwaiti Oil 
Minister 'Ali al-Baghli said in remarks published Sunday [30 
January]. 
  The minister, quoted by the Kuwaiti daily Al-Anba', said a 
cut in output "would be agreed on if OPEC was sure it would lead 
to a bolstering of crude prices." 
  In December the six-nation Gulf Cooperation Council -- 
Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Qatar, Oman and 
Bahrain -- said it was ready to lower production to stabilise 
prices if other producers worldwide pledged to do the same. 
  Omani Oil Minister Sa'id Bin-Ahmad al-Shanfari recently 
toured producers outside the Organisation of Petroleum Exporting 
Countries to seek their support for the GCC [Gulf Cooperation 
Council] offer, but his initiative has not affected the oil 
markets. 
  OPEC members fear a resumption of oil exports by Iraq, 
suspended under the embargo imposed on Baghdad after its 
invasion of Kuwait in August 1990, may push oil prices to new 
lows. 
  Last month they fell to their lowest level in five years, 
deepening a trend that began in the second half of 1993 due to 
excess supply, recession in industrial states and the spectre of 
Iraq's return to the oil market. 
  "OPEC will hold an extraordinary meeting immediately the 
embargo on Iraqi oil is lifted," al-Baghli said. 
  Iraq hopes the oil embargo will be lifted this year, 
following its acceptance in November of long-term weapons 
monitoring -- one of the Gulf war ceasefire conditions laid down 
by the United Nations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-33788 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes021_o_94001" </HT>


