<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delegation Cited on Rabbani, Hekmatyar Resignations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK3001112794 Peshawar THE FRONTIER POST in English 30 Jan 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> BK3001112794 </F>
<F P=104>  Peshawar THE FRONTIER POST </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Afghan prime minister. Eng. Golboddin 
Hekmatyar, has intensified the last week launched diplomatic 
offensive against president Prof Borhanoddin Rabbani and his 
close associate commander Ahmad Shah Mas'ud. 
  A four-member delegation of the Supreme Coordination Council 
arrived in Islamabad last week to meet the foreign minister and 
other concerned officials. The Council consists of Hezb-e 
Eslami, Junbish-e Milli, Hezb-e Wahdat and Afghan National 
Liberation Front. 
  The delegation members were Abdol Hadi Arghandiwal, 
Hashmatollah Mujadadi, Dr Talib and Abdol Samad. During their 
meeting with Foreign Minister Sardar Asif Ali, the delegation 
maintained that fighting in Kabul would continue until President 
Rabbani resigned from his office to pave the way for 
establishment of a broadbased interim government in the Afghan 
capital of Kabul. They said Golboddin Hekmatyar was also 
willing to resign from the office of prime minister. The 
Council is also demanding holding of general elections in the 
country within six months to elect the future government of 
Afghanistan. The setting up of a national army is also one of 
the Council's demands which links its four-point plan to 
restoration of peace in Afghanistan. 
  The Council is also ready to surrender all of their arms to 
the Ministry of Defence of the new government. 
  A reliable source told THE FRONTIER POST on Saturday that 
the 
delegation would also be visiting Iran and Saudi Arabia soon to 
win diplomatic support of these two countries to their peace 
plan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

